{"id":"2204.11614","submitter":"Vera Dobos","authors":"Vera Dobos, Andr\\'as Haris, Inga E. E. Kamp, Floris F. S. van der Tak","title":"A target list for searching for habitable exomoons","comments":"accepted for publication in MNRAS, 10 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stac1180","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the habitability of hypothethical moons orbiting known\nexoplanets. This study focuses on big, rocky exomoons that are capable of\nmaintaining a significant atmosphere. To determine their habitability, we\ncalculate the incident stellar radiation and the tidal heating flux arising in\nthe moons as the two main contributors to the energy budget. We use the runaway\ngreenhouse and the maximum greenhouse flux limits as a definition of\nhabitability. For each exoplanet we run our calculations for plausible ranges\nof physical and orbital parameters for the moons and the planet using a Monte\nCarlo approach. We calculate the moon habitability probability for each planet\nwhich is the fraction of the investigated cases that lead to habitable\nconditions. Based on our results, we provide a target list for observations of\nknown exoplanets of which the top 10 planets have more than 50\\% chance for\nhosting habitable moons on stable orbits. Two especially promising candidates\nare Kepler-62~f and Kepler-16~b, both of them with known masses and radii. Our\ntarget list can help to detect the first habitable exomoon.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 25 Apr 2022 12:43:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-06-08"}
